Bombus bifarius.author: Cresson
Bombus bifarius.notes: Habitat:open grassy fields, parks, prairies, shrubs, and mountainous areas

Bombus bohemicus.author: (Cresson)
Bombus bohemicus.notes: Reported as Bombus ashtoni; Habitat: depends on host species though foraging habits differ because it forages strictly on nectar; endangered

Bombus fervidus.author: (Fabricius)
Bombus fervidus.notes: Habitat: temperate savanna, grassland and tall grass biomes; suburban or agricultural developments; common in grazing farmlands

Bombus flavifrons.author: Cresson
Bombus flavifrons.notes: Habitat : occurs at high altitude and latitude; tundra, taiga, mountainous forests and meadows

Bombus frigidus.author: Smith
Bombus frigidus.notes: Habitat: arctic bees occurring in high altitude and latitude areas

Bombus melanopygus.author: Nylander
Bombus melanopygus.notes: Habitat: broad, including dry chaparral in California and humid areas in Pacific Northwest; also occurs in agricultural and urban environs

Bombus mixtus.author: Cresson
Bombus mixtus.notes: Habitat: mountainous habitat, taiga and tundra; grasslands, chaparral, shrublands and meadows

Bombus occidentalis.author: Greene
Bombus occidentalis.notes: Habitat: mixed woodlands, farmlands, urban areas, montane meadows and into the western edge of the prairie grasslands; endangered

Bombus suckleyi.author: Greene
Bombus suckleyi.notes: Habitat: social parasite dependent on B. occidentalis; now endangered

Bombus vosnesenskii.notes: Habitat: widespread in both urban and agricultural environs; used as pollinator in agricultural applications; early emergence and proliferation of this bee is implicated in declining bumblebee biodiversity

Myxicola cf infundibulum.notes: Dr. Leslie Harris, polychaete expert, remarks: "different NEP websites & publications report this soft-sediment worm as both M. infundibulum and M. aesthetica, which is the first part of the confusion. In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces so if our NEP specimens are really the same as an european species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. The second part of the confusion is what to call them. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, and Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP."
